'''Princess Nakatsu''', also known as '''Nakatsu-hime no Mikoto''', is a figure in [[Japanese mythology]] who was the consort of [[Emperor Ōjin]] and the mother of [[Emperor Nintoku]].<ref name="sseikatsu">{{Cite web |last=文也 |date=2019-05-26 |title=仲姫命とはどんな人？ |url=https://rekishi.sseikatsu.net/nakahime/ |access-date=2023-01-19 |website=歴史好きブログ |language=ja}}</ref><ref name="日本人名大辞典+plus-2023a" />

==History==
There are few known episodes of Princess Nakatsu's life, but she is venerated as a goddess at [[Hachiman shrine]]s.<ref name="sseikatsu"/>

Princess Nakatsu was the daughter of Hondamawaka no Ō (also known as Hondamawaka no Mikoto), a descendant of [[Emperor Kōshō]] and her mother was Kana-taya hime. Princess Nakatsu was the sister of Takano-iri hime and Otohime. She married Ōjin and had two children, Arata-hime no Mikoto and Emperor Nintoku.<ref name="sseikatsu"/>

Princess Nakatsu is believed to have become empress consort to Emperor Ōjin in the 2nd year of his reign.<ref name="日本人名大辞典+plus-2023a">{{Cite web |last=日本人名大辞典+Plus |first=朝日日本歴史人物事典,デジタル版 |title=仲姫命(なかつひめのみこと)とは？ 意味や使い方 |url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E4%BB%B2%E5%A7%AB%E5%91%BD-1096807 |access-date=2023-01-19 |website=コトバンク |language=ja}}</ref><ref name="sseikatsu"/> According to the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'', her sisters Takano-iri hime and Otohime also became consorts of Emperor Ōjin.<ref name="日本人名大辞典+plus-2023a" /> This was a common practice during this period for sisters to be consorts of the emperor.<ref name="sseikatsu"/>

After the death of Emperor Ōjin, Princess Nakatsu became empress dowager and the mother of the new emperor, Emperor Nintoku.<ref name="sseikatsu"/>

The tomb of Princess Nakatsu is believed to be located at Nakatsu-yama no Misasagi in [[Nara Prefecture]].<ref name="sseikatsu"/>

{{ill|Nakatsuyama Kofun|ja|仲ツ山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakatsuyama Kofun|qq=}} Is a kofun in [[Fujiidera]]. It is said that Nakatsuhime was buried there.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Nakatsuhime-no-mikoto-ryo Kofun{{!}}藤井寺市 |url=https://www.city.fujiidera.lg.jp/kanko/language/english/furuichimoundedtombgroup/1473315515279.html |access-date=2023-10-20 |website=www.city.fujiidera.lg.jp |language=ja}}</ref>

